INSERT INTO `evaluationlisterouge` VALUES (1,1315,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','B2ab(iii)','','stable','NT','(VU) B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii)','','','Hibbertia altigena is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia, Grande Terre. It is found on the edge of forests and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) at an altitudinal range 450-1300 m asl.The threats to Hibbertia altigena are likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to mining activities. Population size reduction cannot be assessed because of a lack of data. Its area of occupancy and extent of occurrence are respectively 244 km2 and 7,619 km2. The number of locations, based on habitat degradation as the main threat, is higher than 10. A continuing decline of the quality of habitat is projected. Using criteria B, H. altigena does qualify for Near Threatened (NT) close to Vulnerable (VU) B1ab(iii)&2ab(iii). Population size of mature individuals is unknown.','Répartition assez vaste / population assez éparses, difficile de délimiter des sous-populations / Menace cerf pas directement constatée','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia altigena is an endemic tree widely spread on ultramafic substrate on the main island of New Caledonia, Grande Terre.','','It is found on the edge of forests and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) at an altitudinal range 450-1300 m asl.',7619,244,450,1300,'','Population size is unknown.',0,'inférieur à 30',0,'inférieur à 20','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','The threats to Hibbertia altigena are likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to mining activities.','','Hibbertia altigena is not protected by legislation. It occurs in some protected areas (réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve naturelle du massif du  Kouakoué, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources,réserve naturelle de la Haute Dumbéa, réserve naturelle du Mont Do, réserve naturelle de la Haute Pourina).',''),(2,319,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia baudyesnii is an endemic tree of New Caledonia which appears to be restricted to the southern massifs of the main island, Grande Terre. With an EOO of 1,927 km2, an AOO of 96 km2 and around 12 known sub-populations (some of which occur within a protected area) Hibbertia baudyesnii is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia baudyesnii is an endemic tree of New Caledonia which appears to be restricted to the southern massifs of the main island, Grande Terre.','','Hibbertia baudyesnii occurs in dense humid forest and in middle and high altitude shrubland on ultramafic soils.',1927,96,500,1480,'','Population size is unknown, but H. baudyesnii is quite abundant when found.',0,'inférieur à 20',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','For each known station, H.baudouinii is quite abundant and does not seem threatened.','','Hibbertia baudouinii is not protected by legislation. It occurs in some protected areas (réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve naturelle du massif du  Kouakoué, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources,réserve naturelle de la fausse Yaté, réserve naturelle du Mont Do, réserve naturelle de la Haute Pourina).',''),(3,3602,'Global','2015-04-27','CR','B1ab(v)+2ab(v); C2a(ii)','','decreasing','CR','B1ab(iii,v); C2a(i)','','','Hibbertia bouletii is an endemic tree known from two stations located in the Plaine des lacs area : north riverbank of lac de Yaté and at the confluence between the Riviere des Lacs and the Creek Pernod. Those two sub-populations are considered severely fragmented as they are separeted by the lake. It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on hydromorphic ferralitic soils on an altitudinal range 170-200 m asl. Its area of occupancy (AOO) as its extent of occurence (EOO) is 20 km². The threats to Hibbertia bouletii are more likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to water level fluctuations,  erosion, fire and mining activities (exploration included). Since dam filling, a continuing decline of quality of habitat and number of mature individuals is observed. A count of two sub-populations highlighted a very small size of population : about 30 for the north station and 20 for the south one. Using criteria B and C, H. bouletii does qualify for Critically Endangered (CR) B1ab(iii,v); C2a(i). ','Testé en multiplication chez VALE & IAC (germination maîtrisée) /  Il y en avait a priori dans le lac de Yaté recouvert d\'eau/\nEtudier un statut de protection d\'espace (inclusion dans Ramsar)  / Prospection en aval confluence de pernod et lac Yaté, prospection berges hautes de la rivière Yaté , prospection zone sur le fond du creek qui va être exploité (emprise des ruissellements)/  Espèce à inscrire sur liste de sesp. Protégées / Plantation ex-situ pour multiplication active / Renforcement des populations in -situ / Préservation du milieu rivulaire ( actions amont-aval) / Intéressant d\'étudier la proximité sur le plan phylogénétique entre H. bouletii et H. tontoutensis','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia bouletii is an endemic tree known from two stations located in the Plaine des lacs area : north riverbank of lac de Yaté and at the confluence between the Rivière des Lacs and the Creek Pernod. ','','It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on hydromorphic ferralitic soils at an altitudinal range 170-200 m asl.',20,20,170,200,'','Population size is not precisely known but a count of two sub-populations highlighted a very small size of population : about 30 for the north station and 20 for the south one. We can confidently estimate that there are fewer than 250 mature individuals.',2,'',1,'','','yes',0,'','no','no','no','yes','no','yes','','','','Observed','','Observed','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','The threats to Hibbertia bouletii are linked to habitat degradation due to water level fluctuations,  erosion, fire and mining activities (exploration included). Since dam filling , a continuing decline of quality of habitat and number of mature individuals is observed. An important threat to biodiversity in New Caledonia comes from past, present and future mining activities. New Caledonia contains between 20 - 30% of the world’s nickel resources. Intense mining activities since the late 19th century has generated soil erosion (1.2% of bare ground mapped by SPOT5 in 2007). Based on the distribution of metal-rich soils and site accessibility, these threats are predictable and planned (rise in nickel production from 60,000 to 200,000 tonnes per year between 2013 and 2015).','','H. bouletii is included in the area covered by the Ramsar Convention. In september 2014, 40 plants, multiplicated by the mining company Vale, were planted in two sectors of the Parc Provincial de la Rivière Bleue. To date (July 2015), only 10 individuals are still living. This species would benefit from in-situ and ex-situ emergency conservations actions, and protection of its rivarian habitat ( upriver,down-river). It is moreover recommended to prospect actively H. bouletii in the part of Creek Pernod, which is expected to be exploited, in the area downstream section between lac de Yaté and creek Pernod, and finally on the riverbank of Yaté river. Include this species in the list of protected species may be beneficial.',''),(4,320,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','D1','Pas de menace identifiées mais peu de régénération, nb localités = nb sous-population','stable','NT','(VU) D2','','','Hibbertia comptonii is a rare endemic tree restricted to the Central Chain of  Grande Terre from massif Inédète to Diahoué, corresponding to five sub-populations. It occurs in dense humid forest on volcano-sedimentary substrate on an altitudinal range 500-1000 m asl. Some fire caused by storm could occur in Massif Inédète, but a continuing decline can not be highlighted.\nPopulation size of mature individuals is unknown but it would be plausible that it ranges between 500 and 1,500 and its area of occupancy (AOO) is 24 km². A monitoring of the population is highly recommended as a lack of regeneration is observed for all sub-populations without the possibility of lincking it with any kind of threats. Using criteria D, H. comptonii does qualify for Near Threatened, close to Vulnerable (VU) D2.','prospection à accentuer, avoir des données sur régénération','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia comptonii is an endemic tree restricted to northeast Central Chain of Grande Terre from Massif Inédète to Diahoué in Pouebo.','','It occurs in dense humid forest on volcano-sedimentary substrate at an altitudinal range 500-1000 m asl. ',216,24,500,1000,'','Population size is precisely unknown but it could range between 500 and 1,500 mature individuals.',5,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,1,0,'','On the basis of data available, lack of regeneration observed for all sub-populations can not be linked particularly to any threat. Some fire caused by storm on Massif Inédète could however affect some sub-populations. Quality of habitat for every sub-population looks stable.','','H.comptonii is not protected by legislation. One population occurs in a protected area :  réserve de nature sauvage du Mont Panié.',''),(5,2443,'Global','2015-04-27','VU','C2a(i)','','decreasing','NT','(VU) B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii)','','','Hibbertia deplancheana is an endemic tree mainly spread on ultramafic mountains of north-west Grande Terre . Its area of extension stretches from Poya to Poum with one collect coming from Col d\'Amoss and a second from vallée de Tontouta.  H.deplancheana occurs in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) and on micaschist for the sample of Col d\'Amoss at an altitudinal range 1-700 m asl (rocky slopes). Threats to Hibbertia deplancheana are likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to mining activities and fire.\nPopulation size reduction cannot be assessed because of a lack of data. Its area of occupancy and extent of occurrence are respectively 176 km2 and 3,295 km2. The number of locations, based on habitat degradation as the main threat, is about 15. A continuing decline of the quality of habitat is projected. Using criteria B, H. deplancheana does qualify for Near Threatened (NT) close to Vulnerable (VU) B1ab(iii)&2ab(iii). ','attention début de spéciation  sur les massifs isolés (proposer étude génétique)','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia deplancheana is an endemic tree mostly spread on ultramafic mountains of North-West Grande Terre . Its area of extension stretches from Poya to Poum with one collect coming from Col d\'Amoss on the east coast.  ','','H.deplancheana occurs in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) and on micaschist for the sample of Col d\'Amoss at an altitudinal range 1-700 m asl (rocky slopes).',3295,176,1,700,'','Population size is unknown but H. deplancheana is relatively common on west coast on ultramafic substrate.',15,'',15,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Main threat identified is linked to habitat degradation and reduction due to mining activities and uncontrolled fires that sweep across New Caledonia. The resulting effects of mining activities namely erosion and urbanisation on the sector Voh-Koné-Pouembout and Koumac are not inconsiderable threat.','','H.deplancheana is not protected by legislation and does not occur in any protected area.',''),(6,3603,'Global','2015-04-27','VU','C2a(i)','moins de 1000 indiv par sous-pop\nLors atelier, requestionner le déclin continu (feux, érosion, face à la régénration)','unknown','NT','(VU) B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii)','','','Hibbertia ebracteata is an endemic tree restricted to the southern third of the main island, Grande Terre. It is found on the edge of forests and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) at an altitudinal range 50-1200 m asl. Threats to Hibbertia ebracteata are likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to past mining activities and fire, both resulting in soil erosion.\nPopulation size reduction cannot be assessed because of a lack of data. Its area of occupancy and extent of occurrence are respectively 68 km2 and 1,722 km2. The number of locations, based on habitat degradation as the main threat, is about 20. A continuing decline of the quality of habitat is projected. Using criteria B, H. ebracteata does qualify for Near Threatened (NT) close to Vulnerable (VU) B1ab(iii)&2ab(iii). Population size of mature individuals is unknown.\n','Déclin continu du nb d\'individus no attesté (d\'où l\'impossibilité d\'utiliser le critère C),  regénération faible car pieds isolés\nProspecter zones intermédiaires','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia ebracteata is an endemic tree restricted to the southern third of the main island, Grande Terre.','','It is found on the edge of forests and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) at an altitudinal range 50-1200 m asl.',1722,68,50,1200,'','Population size  cannot be assessed because of a lack of data.',0,'inférieur à 30',0,'inférieur à 30','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Main threats identified is linked to habitat degradation due to past mining activities and fire, both resulting in soil erosion. An important threat to biodiversity in New Caledonia comes from past, present and future mining activities. New Caledonia contains between 20 - 30% of the world’s nickel resources. Intense mining activities since the late 19th century has generated soil erosion (1.2% of bare ground mapped by SPOT5 in 2007). Based on the distribution of metal-rich soils and site accessibility, these threats are predictable and planned (rise in nickel production from 60,000 to 200,000 tonnes per year between 2013 and 2015).','','Hibbertia ebracteata is not protected by legislation. It occurs in some protected areas (réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt,  réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources,réserve naturelle du barrage de Yaté, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Cachée).  It is recommended to prospect the area between known stations to check the species presence.',''),(7,3604,'Global','2015-04-27','EN','B1ab(v)+2ab(v); C2a(i)','','decreasing','VU','C2a(i)','','','H. emarginata is an endemic tree of New Caledonia  restricted to the south half of the main island Grand Terre with Mont Ménazi as a north border. It is found in humid forest and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 700-1300 asl. A continuing decline of the number of mature individuals is inferred by mining activities on Mont Ménazi and Camp des sapins and the lack of regeneration observed. In any sub-population, only isolated tree are found and the total population is estimated to be less than 10,000 mature individuals. Using criteria C, H.emarginata does qualify for Vulnerable (VU) C2a(i).','sommet Ningua plus sec, manque de prospection : réponse T. Leborgne \"n’est ni référencé sur les listes de la SLN concernant l’exploitation à 15 ans du camp des Sapins, ni répertorié dans le cadre des inventaires de la réserve du Ningua. \"Pourtant observé par JLR en 2006 sur camp des sapins. Etendre la prospection sur zone à éboulis, pentes.\nà revoir dans 1-2 ans  pour apprécier','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','H. emarginata is an endemic tree of New Caledonia  restricted to the south half of the main island Grand Terre with Mont Ménazi as a north border. ','','It is found in humid forest and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 700-1300 asl. ',1989,76,700,1300,'','In any sub-population, only isolated tree are found and a lack of regeneration is observed. Total population is estimated to be fewer than 10,000 mature individuals. ',9,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','On the basis of available data, the lack of regeneration observed for all sub-populations can not be linked to threats clearly identified. Nevertheless for the sub-populations of Mont Ménazi, Camp des sapins, Prokomeo and Me Aiu, mining activities could be the reason of decline on those stations. Fire may also affect H.emarginata. ','','H.emarginata is not protected by legislation. It occurs in some protected areas (réserve naturelle du massif du  Kouakoué, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources, réserve naturelle du Mont Do, réserve naturelle de la Haute Pourina). In the known stations, it is recommended to extend prospection on slopes and rock slides to check the species presence.',''),(8,3605,'Global','2015-04-27','CR','B1ab(v)+2ab(v); C2a(ii); D','Possiblement éteint, recherches à mener en urgence dans le secteur (aval et amont)','decreasing','CR','B1ab(iii,v); C2a(ii); D','','','Hibbertia favieri is an endemic tree known from two stations located in the Plaine des lacs area : north riverbank of lac de Yaté and at the confluence between the Riviere des Lacs and Creek Pernod. Those two sub-populations are considered severely fragmented as they are separated by the lake and the population of Creek Pernod is under extinction. It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on hydromophic ferralitic soils at an altitudinal range 190-240 m asl. Its area of occupancy (AOO) as its extent of occurrence (EOO) is 12 km². The threats to Hibbertia favieri are linked to habitat degradation due to erosion, crumbling, fire and mining activities (exploration included) resulting into a continuing decline of quality of habitat and number of mature individuals. Observations on two sub-populations report a total population size fewer than 50 mature individuals. Using criteria B, C and D, H. favieri does qualify for (CR) B1 ab(iii,v); C2a(i); D.  ','Etudier un statut de protection d\'espace (inclusion dans Ramsar)  / Prospection en aval confluence de pernod et lac Yaté, prospection berges hautes de la rivière Yaté , prospection zone sur le fond du creek qui va être exploité (emprise des ruissellements)/  Espèce à inscrire sur liste de sesp. Protégées / Plantation ex-situ pour multiplication active / Renforcement des populations in -situ / Préservation du milieu rivulaire ( actions amont-aval) / Mise en place de travaux en pépinère (Pas encore testé en multiplication) ','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia favieri is an endemic tree of New Caledonia known from two stations located in the Plaine des lacs area : north riverbank of lac de Yaté and at the confluence between the Riviere des Lacs and Creek Pernod. Those two sub-populations are separated by the lac de Yaté. ','','It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on hydromorphic ferralitic soils at an altitudinal range 190-240 m asl.',12,12,190,240,'','Thanks to recent observations on two sub-populations, total population size is estimated to be fewer than 50 mature individuals.',2,'',1,'','','yes',0,'1-50','no','no','no','yes','no','yes','','','','Projected','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Hibbertia favieri may be impacted by uncontrolled bushfire, mining activities (exploration included) and its resulting effects, namely erosion and crumbling. An important threat to biodiversity in New Caledonia comes from past, present and future mining activities. New Caledonia contains between 20 - 30% of the worlds nickel resources. Intense mining activities since the late 19th century generated soil erosion (1.2% of bare ground mapped by SPOT5 in 2007). Based on the distribution of metal-rich soils and site accessibility, these threats are predictable and planned (rise in nickel production from 60,000 to 200,000 tonnes per year between 2013 and 2015). The two known subpopulations of this species are situated on mining concessions (Ouazangou, Mine Saint-Louis) and could be impacted by direct consequences of the mining of ultramafic soils. ','','H.favieri is not protected by legislation but is included in the area covered by The Ramsar Convention. This species would benefit from in-situ and ex-situ emergency conservations actions, and protection of its rivarian habitat ( upriver,down-river). To date, no test on vegetative multiplication has been recorded. It is moreover recommended to prospect actively H. favieri in the part of Creek Pernod, which is expected to be exploited, in the area downstream section between lac de Yaté and creek Pernod, and finally on the riverbank of Yaté river. Include this species in the list of protected species may be beneficial. ',''),(9,3606,'Global','2015-04-27','VU','B1ab(iii,v)+2ab(iii,v); C2a(i)','','decreasing','VU','C2a(i)','','','H. heterotricha is an endemic tree of New Caledonia spread on five sectors on the main island, Grande Terre, with Boulinda-Paéoua-Koépto as the north limit and Montagne des sources as the south one. Tree of open vegetation, H. heterotricha is found in sclerophyllous ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic soils at an altitudinal range 800-1200 m asl. Part of population is under threat of mining activities,  so a continuing decline is estimated because of the resulting degradation of habitat. Total population is estimated to be fewer than 10,000 mature individuals and each sub-population fewer than 1,000. Using criteria C, H. heterotricha does qualify for Vulnerable C2a(i).','pas de fragmentation sevère donc pas possible utiliser critère B (a)/ Menacé par la mine (camps de sapins, à vérifier, étudeSLN) /Surtout effets induits de la mine (sur serpentine), plus vulnérable à séchéresse','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','H. heterotricha is an endemic tree of New Caledonia  spread on five sectors on the main island, Grande Terre, with Boulinda-Paéoua-Koépto as the north limit and Montagne des sources as the south one. ','',' H. heterotricha is found in sclerophyllous ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic soils at an altitudinal range 800-1200 m asl. ',4628,124,100,1100,'','On the basis of 10 known sub-populations, population size of H. heterotricha is estimated to be fewer than 10,000 mature individuals and each sub-population fewer than 1,000.',10,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Projected','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','An important threat to biodiversity in New Caledonia comes from past, present and future mining activities. New Caledonia contains between 20 - 30% of the worlds nickel resources. Intense mining activities since the late 19th century generated soil erosion (1.2% of bare ground mapped by SPOT5 in 2007). Based on the distribution of metal-rich soils and site accessibility, these threats are predictable and planned (rise in nickel production from 60,000 to 200,000 tonnes per year between 2013 and 2015). Three out of five sectors which host Hibbertia heterotricha are actively mined. Perturbations caused by mining activities could also lead to a greater sensitivity to drought.','','H. heterotricha is not protected by legislation but occurs in some protected areas (réserve naturelle du Pic Ningua, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources). In case of reopening of the mine, it would be necessary to carefully prospect the area.',''),(10,3607,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','Prospecter le GdSud (octobre à janvier), pas possible ACD car pas de connaissance pop, pas possible B car plus de 10 localités et pas de E','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia lanceolata is an endemic tree discontinuously distributed on the main island of New Caledonia and on île des Pins. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 10,695 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 52 km2 and probably more than the 11 known subpopulations, Hibbertia lanceolata is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','Prospecter le GdSud, voir si elle est présente dans des réserves. ','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia lanceolata is an endemic tree of New Caledonia widely spread on the main island.','','It is found in ligno-herbaceous shrubland and at the edge of humid forest on ultramafic soils at an altitudinal range 20-850 m asl. ',10695,52,20,850,'','Population size is unknown. The individuals found are mostly isolated plant.',0,'inférieur à 20',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','H.lanceolata may be affected by fire and mining activities. However, it has a large distribution and it does not seem threatened.','','H.lanceolata is not protected by legislation and does not occur in any protected area.',''),(11,809,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','Intéressant de mener des études ADN pour délimiter éventuellement des sous-espèces','increasing','LC','','','','Hibbertia lucens is an autochtonous tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia and abundant in Fiji. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 15,964 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 372 km2 and around 30 known subpopulations, Hibbertia lucens is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','Mener études phylogénétiques pour délimiter des potentiels sous-espèces /  Intéressant d\'étudier la proximité sur le plan phylogénétique entre H. moratii et H. lucens\nFidji, sur quel substrat, quelle altitude ? Stéphane MC se renseigne.','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia lucens is an autochtonous tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia and abundant in Fiji.','','In New Caledonia, it is found in shrubland and humid forest on ultramafic soils, as well as in humid forest on volcano-sedimentary substrate, at an altitudinal range 1-1000 m asl. ',15964,372,1,1000,'','Population size is unknown. As it is frequently a pioneer species on damaged formations, we can estimate that population size is increasing.',30,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,0,1,'','',1,1,0,0,'','By the past, H.luncens was threatened by logging industry. Nowadays, it does not seem threatened.','','H.lucens is not protected by legislation but occur in large number of protected areas (réserve naturelle du Cap N’Dua, réserve naturelle des Chutes de la Madeleine,  réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle de la Vallée de la Thy, Parc provincial de la Rivière Bleue, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Nord, réserve naturelle du pic du grand Kaori, réserve naturelle du Massif du Kouakoué, Mont Do, Mont Mou ).',''),(12,3608,'Global','2015-04-27','EN','D','Mener prospection','unknown','EN','D','','','Hibbertia margaretae is an endemic tree discovered for the first time in Haute Combyes and more recently observed on Mont Humboldt.  It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 900-1390 m asl.  Its area of occupancy (AOO) and extent of occurence (EOO) are respectively 12 km² and 26 km². H.margaretae remains rather protected from the usual threats occurring in New-Caledonia. Nevertheless, population size is estimated to be fewer than 250 mature individuals. Using criteria D, H. margaretae does qualify for Endangered (EN) D. ','aggrandissement de l\'aire de répartition avec le point de JPB à 1390 . Prospecter le Kouakoué qui pourrait abriter cette espèce. Proposer inscription de cette espèce sur la lsite des espèces protégées.','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia margaretae is an endemic tree discovered for the first time in Haute Combyes (1970) and more recently observed on Mont Humboldt. ','','It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 900-1340 m asl. ',26,12,900,1390,'','Within two sub-populations, total population size is estimated to be fewer than 250 mature individuals.',2,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','H.margaretae remains rather protected from the usual threats occurring in New-Caledonia. The presence of ferns on both stations indicates fires in the past, certainly caused by storm. Those bushfires could affect H.margaretae but at the moment there is no evidence of this threat.','','H.margaretae is not protected by legislation but occurs in one protected area : the réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt. As it has not been not been recorded from Kouakoué massifs which has similar eco-geographic conditions as the existing sub-populations, it is recommended to investigate this area. Include this species in the list of protected species may be beneficial. ',''),(13,3609,'Global','2015-04-27','VU','D1','A rechercher sur autres massifs autour Boulinda\nJM a doutes génétiques avec Lucens','stable','VU','D1','','','Hibbertia moratii, endemic altimontane species of New Caledonia, is restricted on northwestern moutains of the main island, namely Boulinda and Paéoua massifs. It occurs in dense humid forest and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 800-1200 m asl. Owing to its altitudinal range, we can consider that mining activites and fire do not constitute direct threats to H. moratii. However, with only two known sub-populations, it is estimated that population size ranges under 1,000.  Using criteria D, H. moratii does qualify for Vulnerable (VU D1). It is recommended to monitor the population because a further reopening of the mine on Boulinda massif could rapidly endanger this species.','prospection à accentuer autour du petit Boulinda. Possibilité de mise en réserve. / Intéressant d\'étudier la proximité sur le plan phylogénétique entre H. moratii et H. lucens','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','H. moratii is an endemic altimontane species of New Caledonia restricted on northwestern moutains of the main island, namely Boulinda and Paéoua massifs.','','It occurs in dense humid forest and in shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 800-1200 m asl. ',39,24,800,1200,'','With only two known sub-populations, it is estimated that population size ranges under 1,000 mature individuals.',2,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Owing to its altitudinal range,mining activities does not constitute direct threats to H. moratii. Some fires have been recorded on Boulinda in the past, but it seems that they did not affect H.moratii population. Uncontrolled bushfires sweep across New Caledonia each year, especially during the dry season (an average of 20,000 ha of land is burnt each year, with dramatic peaks of 70,000 ha). They contribute to habitat fragmentation and decline in the quality of habitat.','','H.moratii is protected in Province Nord but does not occur in any protected area.  It is recommended to monitor the population because a further reopening of the mine on Boulinda massif could rapidly endanger this species.',''),(14,2477,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','D2','','stable','NT','(VU) D2','','','Hibbertia nana is an endemic tree restricted to the southern third of the main island Grand Terre. It is found in shrubland on ultramafic substrate or outcrop of peridotite at an altitudinal range 500-1500 m asl. Its area of occupancy (AOO) and extent of occurence (EOO) are respectively 36 km² and 197 km². Old signs of fire, recent wind erosion and water stress are observed, but a continuing decline can not be highlighted. However climate change would considerably affect H.nana as there would be no more suitable habitat for H.nana.\nWithin five known sub-populations, population size of mature individuals is unknown but it would be plausible that it ranges around 2,000 mature individuals. Using criteria D, H. nana does qualify for Near Threatened, close to Vulnerable (VU) D2.\n','peu de régénration observée/évidente (classique en maquis d\'altitude)\nmenace changement climatique/érosion/pluviométrie','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia nana is an endemic tree restricted to the southern third of the main island Grand Terre. All collections come from three sectors geographycally close : Montagne des Sources, Humboldt-Colde Ni-Kouakoué, Haute Tontouta-Combyes.','','It is found in shrubland on ultramafic substrate or outcrop of peridotite an altitudinal range 700-1500 m asl. ',197,36,700,1500,'','Population size of mature individuals is unknown but it would be plausible that it ranges around 2,000. The regeneration observed is quite low, but seems normal for altimontane shrubland species.',5,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Some old signs of fire are recorded without direct impact on H. nana. The main threats to H.nana are linked to climate change and its consequences on wind erosion and pluviometry. Climate change would considerably affect H.nana as there would be no more suitable habitat for H.nana.','','H.nana is not protected by legislation but occurs in three protected areas : réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources and réserve naturelle du massif du Kouakoué.',''),(15,2401,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia pancheri is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 15,690 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 492 km2 and  more than 100 known stations, Hibbertia pancheri is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','Sert de support (de même que les espèces du genre Nothofagus) à la chenille du papillon Aenatus cohici','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia pancheri is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia.','','H. pancheri is found on shrubland, edge on forest and humid forest preferentially on ultramafic soils.',15690,492,1,1100,'','Population size is unknown. When present, this species is abundant.',0,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Mining activities may affect H.pancheri.','','H.pancheri is not protected by legislation but occurs in several protected areas (réserve naturelle du Cap N’Dua, réserve naturelle des Chutes de la Madeleine,  réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle de la Vallée de la Thy, Parc provincial de la Rivière Bleue, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Nord, réserve naturelle du pic du grand Kaori, réserve naturelle du Massif du Kouakoué, réserve naturelle du Mont Do, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve de nature sauvage du mont Panié, Réserve de nature sauvage du massif de l’Aoupinié,Vallée de la Thy, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Cachée, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt).',''),(16,3610,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','D2','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia patula is an endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the southern part of the main island, Grande Terre. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 2,538 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 88 km2 and around 12 known subpopulations, some of which occur within a protected area, Hibbertia patula is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia patula is an endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the southern part of the main island, Grande Terre, with Presqu\'île de Bogota as eastern border.','','H. patula is found on ligno-herbaceous shrubland and humid forest on ultramafic soils at an altitudinal range 150 - 1200 asl.',2538,88,150,1200,'','Population size is unknown. This species is always found as isolated plant.',10,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Fire may affect some sub-populations on ligno-herbaceous shrubland (three out of 10 sub-populations). ','','H.patula is not protected by legislation but it occurs in several protected areas (réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve naturelle du Massif du Kouakoué, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources, Parc Provincial de la Rivière Bleue, réserve naturelle du Barrage de Yaté, réserve naturelle de la Fausse Yaté, réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille,réserve naturelle de la Haute Pourina).',''),(17,2444,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia podocarpifolia is an endemic tree spread on the main island of New Caledonia from Dumbéa to Koné. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 8,138 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 188 km2 and around 20 known subpopulations, Hibbertia podocarpifolia is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia podocarpifolia is an endemic tree spread on the main island of New Caledonia from Dumbéa to Koné. It is a common species on the east coast.','','H. podocarpifolia is found in shrubland and humid forest on ultramafic soils at an altitudinal range 1 - 1100 m asl. It can also be found on riverside forest.',8138,188,1,1100,'','Population size is unknown.',0,'inférieur à 30',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Mining activities may affect H. podocarpifolia. As a riparian species, population of H. podocarpifolia located on riverbank can be affected by erosion caused by heavy rain.','','H.podocarpifolia is not protected by legislation but it occurs in protected areas (Parc des Grandes Fougères,réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle du Pic Ningua, réserve naturelle du Mont Do, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou).',''),(18,1317,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia pulchella is an endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the southern part of the main island, Grande Terre. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 1,524 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 68 km2 and around 15 known subpopulations, some of which occur within a protected area, Hibbertia pulchella is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','l\'espèce se bouture plus ou moins facilement et la croissance est très médiocre en pépinière, peu de fruits par inflorescence (travaux IAC), utilisé en revégét par Vale (Gildas, Stéphane).','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia pulchella is a common endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the south of the main island, Grande Terre.','','H. pulchella is mostly found on ligno-herbaceous shrubland on hydromorphic ferralitic soils but also in open vegetation on ultramafic soils, at an altitudinal range 30 - 700 asl.',1524,68,30,700,'','Population size may be higher than 10,000 mature individuals. When present in a station, H. pulchella is abundant.',15,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','H.pulchella seems to remain rather protected from the usual threats occurring in New Caledonia.','','H.pulchella is not protected by legislation but it occurs in several protected areas (réserve naturelle du Massif du Kouakoué, réserve naturelle de la Haute Dumbéa,réserve naturelle des Chutes de la Madeleine, aire de gestion durable des ressources de Netcha,Parc Provincial de la Rivière Bleue, réserve naturelle du Barrage de Yaté, réserve naturelle de la Fausse Yaté, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Cachée, réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille).',''),(19,3611,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','','','unknown','VU','D2','','','H.rubescens is an endemic tree of New Caledonia restricted to a shrubland located on the slopes of Massif Taom. It precisely occurs at an altitudinal range 200-700 m asl. Population size reduction cannot be assessed because of a lack of data but it would be plausible that it ranges over 1,000.  A geographical barriers between Ouazangou and Taom seems to preserve H.rubescens from mining activity located on near massif. However, monitoring of the situation (impact of mine\'s reopening anf bushfire ) is highly recommended as this microendemic species is Vulnerable (VU D2) because of its tiny area of occupancy (AOO). ','prospection manque pour avoir une idée. projet sur Mont Taom, menace plausible en cas de reprise minière (et donc effet induit d\'ouverture de piste) car le taxon pourrait très vite aller vers EN et CR. important d\'informer la société civile de la présence de cette population sur Mt Taom. Si reprise mine, possibilité de mise en défens d\'une partie du milieu hébergeant le peuplement.','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','H.rubescens is an endemic tree of New Caledonia restricted to a shrubland located on the slopes of Massif Taom.','','It occurs on shrubland, mostly dominated by Gymnostoma chamaecyparis on altered peridotite at an altitudinal range 200-700 m asl.',20,20,200,700,'','Population size is estimated higher than 1,000 mature individuals.',1,'',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','Uncontrolled bushfires sweep across New Caledonia each year, especially during the dry season (an average of 20,000 ha of land is burnt each year, with dramatic peaks of 70,000 ha). They contribute to habitat fragmentation and decline in the quality of habitat. Some fire observed on west downward slope of Mount Taom may affect H. rubescens. However, reopening mining activities remains the main threat. Planned exploitation for nickel, on the ultramafic massif Mont Taom will very likely result in a decline in the extent and quality of habitat and decline of mature individuals in the foreseeable future. Monitoring of the situation is highly recommended as this microendemic species is Vulnerable (VU D2) because of its tiny area of occupancy (AOO).','','H. rubescens is protected by legislation in Province Nord. It does not occur in any protected areas. To avoid any risks of fire, it is recommended to inform the department of civil defense that H. rubescens is present on Mont Taom. It would also be benefical to put under protection a part of its habitat.',''),(20,2445,'Global','2015-04-27','EN','B1ab(iii,v)+2ab(iii,v); C2a(i)','La recherche dans le Sud (notamment Creek Pernod)','decreasing','EN','B1ab(iii,v)+2ab(iii,v)','','','Hibbertia tontoutensis is an endemic tree found in abundance in basse vallée de Tontouta and in the surroudings area as well as in Plaine des lacs area. It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 20-760 m asl.  Its area of occupancy (AOO) and extent of occurrence (EOO) are respectively 56 km² and 935 km². Most of the population is gathered on the riverbank of Tontouta river, which is a locality directly impacted by mining activities. The population of creek Pernod locality is also under extinction due to induced effects of mine. The three other localities are : forêt de Thy, Ouénarou and Yaté. Due to the mining activities, resulting erosion and regularly eroded riverbank, a continuing decline of quality of habitat and mature individuals is inferred. Using criteria B, H. tontoutensis does qualify for Endangered (EN) B1ab(iii,v)&2ab(iii,v).','régénération faible / Parfaire connaissance sur répartition (creek Pernod, affluents Tontouta…) / prospecter rivière Kalouehola et zone à H. favieri au niveau du creek Pernod, et chutes de la Madeleine /\"l\'espèce se bouture et se cultive bien.\nIl lui faut de la lumière et une bonne irrigation sino elle dépérit dans un massif pas irrigué et trop à l\'ombre.\"(Gildas G.) / Intéressant d\'étudier la proximité sur le plan phylogénétique entre H. bouletii et H. tontoutensis\n','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia tontoutensis is an endemic tree found in abundance in basse vallée de Tontouta and in the surroudings area as well as in Plaine des lacs area. ','',' It occurs in ligno-herbaceous shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 20-760 m asl. ',996,52,20,760,'','Population size is estimated to be fewer than 2,500 mature individuals with a drecreasing of population size for the sub-population on ferralitic soil. The biggest part of population is located on riverbank of Tontouta river. Low regeneration is observed (no apparent reasons).',5,'',5,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','yes','no','yes','','','','Inferred','','Inferred','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','This species occurs on area intensively mined and impacted by mining activities and related activites like road construction for engines. An important threat to biodiversity in New Caledonia comes from past, present and future mining activities. New Caledonia contains between 20 - 30% of the world’s nickel resources. Intense mining activities since the late 19th century has generated soil erosion (1.2% of bare ground mapped by SPOT5 in 2007). Based on the distribution of metal-rich soils and site accessibility, these threats are predictable and planned (rise in nickel production from 60,000 to 200,000 tonnes per year between 2013 and 2015). Apart from the degradation on concessions, mining activities are resulting on erosion which increase impact on H. tontoutensis. It is recommended to monitor the population to enlarge prospecting on Creek Pernod, tributaries of Tontouta and Kalouehola River to have a precise idea of damage that mining activities are causing.  The sub-populations of forêt de Thy and Yaté do not appear under threat but the sub-population of Ouenarou may affect by bushfire.','','H.tontoutensis is not protected by legislation but occurs in protected areas (réserve naturelle de la Vallée de la Thy, Parc Provincial de la Rivière Bleue, réserve naturelle du Barrage de Yaté).  It is recommended to prospect actively H. tontoutensis on the riverbank of Kalouehola river, where H. favieri is present, and Chutes de la Madeleine. Include this species in the list of protected species may be beneficial. ',''),(21,2446,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','','Prospecter + au Nord (Kaala…) & zones intermédiaires ? Populations du Nord seraient + menacées','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia trachyphylla is an endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the southern and one of northwestern ultramafic massifs of the main island, Grande Terre. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 6,798 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 248 km2 and around 20 known subpopulations, some of which occur within a protected area, Hibbertia trachyphylla is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia trachyphylla is an endemic tree of New Caledonia where it appears to be restricted to the southern and one of northwestern ultramafic massifs of the main island, Grande Terre.','','H. trachyphylla is found at the edge of humid forest and in shrubland on ultramafic soils on an altitudinal range 1-1100 m asl.',6798,248,1,1100,'','Population size is unknown. When present, this species is abundant.',0,'inférieur à 30',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','H. trachyphylla may be affected by mining activities, especially the north sub-population located on massif Koniambo.','','H.trachyphylla is not protected by legislation but occurs in several protected areas (réserve naturelle du Pic Ningua, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou, réserve naturelle de la Haute Dumbéa, réserve naturelle du pic du grand Kaori, réserve naturelle du Pic du Pin,réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources, réserve naturelle des Chutes de la Madeleine, réserve naturelle de la Fausse Yaté, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Cachée, réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle de la Haute Pourina, réserve naturelle de la Haute Yaté, réserve naturelle du Massif du Kouakoué).',''),(22,3612,'Global','2015-04-27','NT','B1ab(iii)','','decreasing','NT','(VU) B1ab(iii)+2ab(iii)','','','Hibbertia vieillardii is an endemic tree mostly spread on southern massifs of the main island, Grande Terre, but also found on Mont Poum and Népyes on northern part.It is found in shrubland on ultramafic substrate (maquis minier) at an altitudinal range 20-1400 m asl.The threats to Hibbertia vieillardii are likely to be linked to habitat degradation due to mining activities, the resulting current degradation in erosion but also fire.\nPopulation size reduction cannot be assessed because of a lack of data. Its area of occupancy and extent of occurrence are respectively 108 km2 and 8,144 km2. The number of locations, based on habitat degradation as the main threat, is about 15. Owing to past and current fire and mining activities, a continuing decline of the quality of habitat is observed and projected. Using criteria B, H. vieillardii does qualify for Near Threatened (NT) close to Vulnerable (VU) B1ab(iii)&2ab(iii). Population size of mature individuals is unknown.','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia vieillardii is an endemic tree mostly spread on southern massifs of the main island, Grande Terre, but also found on Mont Poum and Népyes on northern part.','','It is found in shrubland on ultramafic substrate at an altitudinal range 20-1400 m asl.',8144,108,20,1400,'','Population size is unknown, but a decreasing of the sub-population of Thio due to fire and mining activities in the 1950s is recorded.',12,'',17,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','yes','','','','','','Estimated','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','The main threat identified is linked to habitat degradation and reduction due to uncontrolled fires that sweep across New Caledonia.  The stations of Thio, Canala, Montagne des Sources, Dumbéa and île des Pins may be the most affected. Another second threat comes from mining activities and resulting erosion.','','H.vieillardii is not protected by legislation but occurs in some protected area (réserve naturelle de la forêt de Saille, réserve naturelle de la Haute Dumbéa, réserve intégrale de la Montagne des Sources, réserve naturelle du Mont Humboldt, réserve naturelle du Mont Do).',''),(23,3613,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','','stable','LC','','','','Hibbertia wagapii is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia but also on Belep, Daos, Yandé and Ile des Pins. With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 15,984 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 244 km2 and  around 50 known stations, Hibbertia wagapii is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia wagapii is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia but also on Belep, Daos, Yandé and Ile des Pins.','','H. wagapii occurs on shrubland and at the edge of forest on ultramafic soils, preferentially on downhill serpentinite. More rarely it can be found in northwestern part of the main sland on schist soil.  ',15984,244,1,950,'','H. wagapii is abundant in New Caledonia.',0,'inférieur à 40',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','The main threat identified is linked to habitat degradation and reduction due to mining activities.','','H.wagapii is not protected by legislation but it occurs in some protected areas (réserve nautrelle de la Haute Dumbéa, réserve naturelle du Mont Mou).',''),(24,1934,'Global','2015-04-27','LC','','à chercher à Maré (sur roches madréporiques)','stable','LC','','','','Tetracera billardierei is an endemic species widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia and the surroundings islands (île des Pins, Belep, île Ouen, Tanlé, Balabio). With an extent of occurrence (EOO) of 18,590 km2, an area of occupancy (AOO) of 128 km2 and around 50 known stations, Tetracera billardierei is assigned a status of Least Concern (LC).','serait utilisé en médecine tradi pour stabiliser le diabète.','3.1',1,2015,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Tetracera billardierei is an endemic tree widely spread on the main island of New Caledonia and the surroundings islands (île des Pins, Belep, île Ouen, Tanlé, Balabio). ','','T. billardierei can be found as a bush on open vegetation or secondary forest, or as vine on humid forest on any soil.',18590,128,1,600,'','Tetracera billardierei is abundant in New Caledonia.',0,'inférieur à 40',0,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,0,1,'','T. billardierei is used in traditional medicine to cure diabetes.',1,1,0,0,'','No particular threat has been noticed.','','T. billardierei is not protected by legislation but it occurs in several protected areas (réserve naturelle de la Haute Dumbéa, réserve naturelle de la Vallée de la Thy, Parc Zoologique et Forestier, Le Parc du Ouen Toro - Albert Etuvé et Lucien Audet, réserve naturelle du Cap N’Dua, réserve naturelle de la Forêt Nord, réserve naturelle du pic du grand Kaori,réserve naturelle du Mont Mou).',''),(25,321,'Global','2015-04-27','DD','','','unknown','DD','','','','This species was briefly described on the basis of two collects (MacKee, 27839; Schmid, 2814), which seem conspecific. Only known from two stations, this distinct species from other caledonian species of genus Hibbertia should be subject to further examination. Considering this taxonomic problem, Hibbertia sp. is assigned a status of Data Deficient(DD).','prospection à mener selon les prérogatives de Lowry & Munzinger émises lors de l\'étude Camp des sapins','3.1',0,0000,0,0,0,0,'','','','','Hibbertia sp. is an endemic tree only known from two stations in the south of the main island : Baie de yesnné and Mont Ninga.','','Hibbertia sp. is found in dense shrubland at an altitudinal range 600-700 asl.',8,8,600,700,'','Population size is unknown.',2,'',2,'','','no',0,'','no','no','no','no','no','no','','','','','','','no','no','no','no','no',0,0,0,1,0,'','',1,1,0,0,'','For the population located on Mount Ninga, the threat comes from mining activities.','','This species is not protected by local legislation and does not occur in any protected area. In terms of prospection, it recommended to follow the indications given by the experts Lowry and Munzinger.','');
